{"term": "2012", "caseName": "United States v. Davila", "caseLink": "https://www.oyez.org/cases/2012/12-167", "caseTranscripts": [{"transcriptTitle": "Oral Argument - April 15, 2013", "transcriptLink": "https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/roberts6/oral_argument_audio/22778", "transcript": [{"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "We will hear argument next in Case 12-167, United States v. Davila.", "start": 0, "stop": 5.904, "duration": 5.9}, {"text": "Mr. Feigin?", "start": 5.904, "stop": 7.487, "duration": 1.58}, {"text": "It is Feigin, right?", "start": 7.487, "stop": 8.856, "duration": 1.37}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric J. Feigin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, Your Honor, thank you.", "start": 8.856, "stop": 9.872, "duration": 1.02}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you.", "start": 9.872, "stop": 10.389, "duration": 0.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric J. Feigin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you, Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court:", "start": 10.389, "stop": 13.391, "duration": 3}, {"text": "The court of appeals' practice of automatically granting appellate relief for every violation of Rule 11(c)(1), irrespective whether it prejudiced the defendant, is flawed.", "start": 13.391, "stop": 23.615, "duration": 10.22}, {"text": "As this Court recognized in United States v. Vaughn, Rule 11(h) was adopted for the precise purpose of ending the then-common practice of automatically reversing even for non-prejudicial Rule 11 errors.", "start": 23.615, "stop": 36.339, "duration": 12.72}, {"text": "It would be especially inappropriate to apply an automatic reversal rule in a case like this one that comes to the appellate courts in a plain error posture.", "start": 36.339, "stop": 44.16, "duration": 7.82}, {"text": "Erroneous judicial participation--", "start": 44.16, "stop": 46.095, "duration": 1.94}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "May -- may I ask you a question about that?", "start": 46.095, "stop": 48.481, "duration": 2.39}, {"text": "It's plain error because the defendant didn't make an objection in the lower court.", "start": 48.481, "stop": 56.253, "duration": 7.77}, {"text": "But the defendant doesn't know about Rule 11 and doesn't know about 11(c) that says a judge is not supposed to participate in plea bargaining, and his lawyer doesn't tell him the judge is doing something wrong because his lawyer wants him to plea.", "start": 56.253, "stop": 74.881, "duration": 18.63}, {"text": "So he lacks the information necessary to make a prompt objection.", "start": 74.881, "stop": 80.702, "duration": 5.82}, {"text": "So it seems a bit unfair to say that he's subjected to plain error when he hasn't got a clue that the judge, magistrate wasn't supposed to do what he did.", "start": 80.702, "stop": 94.628, "duration": 13.93}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric J. Feigin", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, first of all, Your Honor, I'd respectfully disagree with the notion that just because Respondent's counsel was advising him to plead guilty, that Respondent's counsel had so advocated -- so abdicated his representation that he couldn't be expected to object to an error that the judge made.", "start": 94.628, "stop": 110.221, "duration": 15.59}, {"text": "I'd also point out that if the Court were to create an exception to the plain error doctrine, this would be a particularly inappropriate case in which to do it because not only was there not a contemporaneous objection, there wasn't an objection before the district judge in the months and proceedings that followed.", "start": 110.221, "stop": 123.695, "duration": 13.47}, {"text": "They didn't raise any claim of error on appeal until the court of appeals raised it.", "start": 123.695, "stop": 128.533, "duration": 4.84}, {"text": "And in fact, in this case, Respondent did file a motion in the district court to withdraw his plea.", "start": 128.533, "stop": 134.503, "duration": 5.97}, {"text": "And he didn't mention the magistrate's comments or any pressure he felt from those comments at all.", "start": 134.503, "stop": 139.074, "duration": 4.57}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, suppose you just stick with Justice Ginsburg's hypothetical, or perhaps not even a hypothetical, what happened in this case.", "start": 139.074, "stop": 145.227, "duration": 6.15}, {"text": "Just assume that the defense attorney likes this judicial intervention and he -- he wants this to take place.", "start": 145.227, "stop": 153.75, "duration": 8.52}, {"text": "It -- it seems quite unfair to talk about the plain error, because he doesn't tell -- as Justice Ginsburg says, what does the defendant know about Rule 11(c)?", "start": 153.75, "stop": 164.439, "duration": 10.69}, {"text": "He doesn't know about it.", "start": 164.439, "stop": 165.391, "duration": 0.95}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric J. Feigin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, Your Honor, if Respondent wants to make an ineffective assistance of counsel claim on collateral review, he can make that.", "start": 165.391, "stop": 172.712, "duration": 7.32}, {"text": "But I'm not aware of any court of appeals that has abandoned the plain error doctrine in this kind of case and I don't think there should be any sort of special exception that says when -- that we assume when counsel is advising his client to plead guilty, that we can't expect counsel to make objections to errors that occur based on the judge's comments.", "start": 172.712, "stop": 191.958, "duration": 19.25}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "It doesn't really matter--", "start": 191.958, "stop": 193.291, "duration": 1.33}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "But this is a lawyer that had filed an Anders brief.", "start": 193.291, "stop": 196.243, "duration": 2.95}, {"text": "So he didn't -- even at that stage, the lawyer, the -- I don't want to absorb your time beyond this, but I think the plain error is questionable when it seems that the judge, the lawyer, they arranged against the -- the defendant, and the defendant doesn't know that he has this route.", "start": 196.243, "stop": 220.693, "duration": 24.45}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric J. Feigin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, Your Honor, let me just say one other word about that.", "start": 220.693, "stop": 223.895, "duration": 3.2}, {"text": "I don't think it's going to be easy for courts of appeals to tell exactly why the lawyer may not have made an objection, and I just don't think it's fair to assume that in every Rule 11(c)(1) case that the lawyer is effectively acting at contrary purposes to his client.", "start": 223.895, "stop": 241.622, "duration": 17.73}, {"text": "I mean, lawyers advise clients to plead guilty all the time and that doesn't mean that they've abandoned the representation to the point where you can't assume they're acting on the client's behalf and will raise objections.", "start": 241.622, "stop": 251.664, "duration": 10.04}, {"text": "But our basic point in this--", "start": 251.664, "stop": 253.347, "duration": 1.68}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Excuse me.", "start": 253.347, "stop": 253.949, "duration": 0.6}, {"text": "Does this issue go -- it doesn't go to whether you should apply the prejudice prong, because either under normal harmless error or plain error you have to get to whether it prejudices someone.", "start": 253.949, "stop": 265.305, "duration": 11.36}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric J. Feigin", "textObjs": [{"text": "--That's exactly right, Justice Sotomayor.", "start": 265.305, "stop": 266.606, "duration": 1.3}, {"text": "That was exactly the next sentence that was going to come out of my mouth is that our basic point in this case is that you have to apply prejudice analysis in some form, and whether it's harmless error or plain error, the court of appeals refuses to do it.", "start": 266.606, "stop": 278.231, "duration": 11.63}, {"text": "And we think--", "start": 278.231, "stop": 278.881, "duration": 0.65}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "One of the most powerful arguments of your adversary is that in the most common of situations -- and it's how I read the advisory notes -- it's going to be awfully difficult to say that a judge's intervention hasn't influenced a defendant.", "start": 278.881, "stop": 297.209, "duration": 18.33}, {"text": "This is the unusual case where you might actually have a no prejudice argument because of the unique facts.", "start": 297.209, "stop": 303.863, "duration": 6.65}, {"text": "But there is a purpose for keeping judges out of this, and that's because the subtle influence that judges exert is not so subtle.", "start": 303.863, "stop": 314.337, "duration": 10.47}, {"text": "It's very palpable and does influence most decision making, both by lawyers and defendants.", "start": 314.337, "stop": 322.676, "duration": 8.34}, {"text": "So if that's the standard, why isn't it a rebuttable presumption that prejudice exists?", "start": 322.676, "stop": 328.764, "duration": 6.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric J. Feigin", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well--", "start": 328.764, "stop": 330.064, "duration": 1.3}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "It has to be an awfully high presumption, otherwise, you make mockery of the rule, in my mind.", "start": 330.064, "stop": 336.318, "duration": 6.25}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric J. Feigin", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, first of all, Your Honor, I want to take issue with the notion that all Rule 11(c)(1) errors are alike.", "start": 336.318, "stop": 341.472, "duration": 5.15}, {"text": "There's actually a variety of different kinds of Rule 11(c)(1) errors.", "start": 341.472, "stop": 344.857, "duration": 3.39}, {"text": "Rule 11(c)(1) has been held to cover, for example, a judge pressuring the government outside the defendant's presence to offer a plea, a judge discouraging a plea, a judge commenting in a well-intentioned manner about the obvious difference in potential sentencing consequences between a potential plea agreement and a trial, or a judge, having rejected one plea agreement that the parties reached, indicating a bit too strongly what kind of plea agreement the judge might accept.", "start": 344.857, "stop": 370.841, "duration": 25.98}, {"text": "I think adopting some sort of “ one size fits all ” rule would -- would be inappropriate, and the rebuttable presumption I think would also be inappropriate, for a few reasons.", "start": 370.841, "stop": 379.18, "duration": 8.34}, {"text": "First of all, I don't think courts should have to distinguish between different types of errors to see whether a rebuttable presumption should apply.", "start": 379.18, "stop": 384.917, "duration": 5.74}, {"text": "Second of all--", "start": 384.917, "stop": 386.084, "duration": 1.17}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, I don't disagree that one doesn't' have to use the word “ rebuttable presumption ”, but there has to be a strong prejudice factor--", "start": 386.084, "stop": 395.724, "duration": 9.64}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric J. Feigin", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, Your Honor--", "start": 395.724, "stop": 396.874, "duration": 1.15}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "--whether rebuttable or not, assumed in a judge's intervention.", "start": 396.874, "stop": 400.01, "duration": 3.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric J. Feigin", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I think that's already built into Rule 52 in a couple of different ways.", "start": 400.01, "stop": 403.628, "duration": 3.62}, {"text": "First of all, Rule 52 places a presumption based on whether or not the defendant objected.", "start": 403.628, "stop": 408.199, "duration": 4.57}, {"text": "If the defendant objected, the burden's on the government.", "start": 408.199, "stop": 411.651, "duration": 3.45}, {"text": "If the defendant didn't object, the burden is on the defendant.", "start": 411.651, "stop": 413.686, "duration": 2.03}, {"text": "But also, I don't -- I want to be clear on this: The type of error -- if there is a very serious error, the nature of the error and the error's seriousness would of course be a factor, and a very important factor, in the prejudice analysis.", "start": 413.686, "stop": 427.161, "duration": 13.48}, {"text": "But, as Your Honor has recognized with this case, there may be other circumstances that indicate that the error did not in this case have a reasonable probability of affecting the decision of the plea.", "start": 427.161, "stop": 437.551, "duration": 10.39}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "But that's the problem.", "start": 437.551, "stop": 438.151, "duration": 0.6}, {"text": "Is there a way of doing this, which I -- I don't see at the moment?", "start": 438.151, "stop": 443.289, "duration": 5.14}, {"text": "But the judge intervenes in a serious way and says, you go listen to your lawyer and this is a very harsh penalty and, boy, you are into -- okay?", "start": 443.289, "stop": 453.395, "duration": 10.11}, {"text": "A serious problem.", "start": 453.395, "stop": 454.93, "duration": 1.54}, {"text": "And now to track down whether that affected substantial rights, you have to try to track down the state of mind of the defendant and would he have pled guilty anyway.", "start": 454.93, "stop": 463.453, "duration": 8.52}, {"text": "And that's sometimes quite difficult to do, very hard.", "start": 463.453, "stop": 467.821, "duration": 4.37}, {"text": "But if you don't insist on doing it, and you have an absolute rule of structural error or something, then you suddenly discover these minor things.", "start": 467.821, "stop": 478.395, "duration": 10.57}, {"text": "The judge says, go to lunch, or -- or, you know, some really trivial intervention, and you are going to say that -- the guilty plea, he can just void his guilty plea.", "start": 478.395, "stop": 487.151, "duration": 8.76}, {"text": "So there should be a way of distinguishing the trivial from the -- from the really important in terms of how serious the intervention was, but I don't see any way to do that.", "start": 487.151, "stop": 496.34, "duration": 9.19}, {"text": "Have -- have you thought about that at all?", "start": 496.34, "stop": 498.024, "duration": 1.68}, {"text": "Do we have to go all the one way or all the other way?", "start": 498.024, "stop": 500.709, "duration": 2.69}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric J. Feigin", "textObjs": [{"text": "I have thought about that a little bit, Your Honor, and I'd say that trying to break Rule 11(c)(1) into different pieces and adopt different rules based on different kinds of error would be inappropriate, for three main reasons.", "start": 500.709, "stop": 512.516, "duration": 11.81}, {"text": "The first one is I think it would be inconsistent with this Court's position in Neder v. the United States, which makes clear that in deciding whether an error is structural you have to look at the entire class of errors.", "start": 512.516, "stop": 521.972, "duration": 9.46}, {"text": "And Rule 11(c)(1) defines the class of errors as cases in which a judge participates in plea negotiations in some way, and it doesn't define subcategories.", "start": 521.972, "stop": 530.645, "duration": 8.67}, {"text": "Second, I think breaking this up into pieces would essentially be an incomplete and unsatisfactory form of prejudice analysis.", "start": 530.645, "stop": 539.417, "duration": 8.77}, {"text": "That is, reviewing courts would still be looking at errors and differentiating between them in order to decide whether relief is warranted, but they would be narrowly focused only on the binary inquiry of how to categorize the error, they'd be disregarding how serious that particular error was versus other errors in that category, and they would be disregarding all the other facts and circumstances the courts always look at and are well familiar with how to look at in a normal prejudice analysis, to determine whether the error affected the outcome.", "start": 539.417, "stop": 565.401, "duration": 25.98}, {"text": "Third, particularly because the subcategories don't exist in the rule and would be something of judicial invention, I think that approach would be inherently inadministrable and manipulatable and lead to inconsistent results.", "start": 565.401, "stop": 578.828, "duration": 13.43}, {"text": "It could be very difficult to tell whether a particular type of error should fall into one category or another, and under the approach you're suggesting, which I think is the approach Respondent is advocating -- I don't think Respondent is actually advocating the per se rule that the Eleventh Circuit adopted here -- I think under that approach, you know, everything turns on a narrow question of categorization.", "start": 578.828, "stop": 599.657, "duration": 20.83}, {"text": "I think the much better approach, and the approach that Rule 52 adopts, is to look at all the facts and circumstances to attempt to determine the effect on the outcome.", "start": 599.657, "stop": 608.18, "duration": 8.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Feigin, is there any situation in which a -- a judge participating in a plea bargaining, any situation that would be prejudicial, that you recognize would be prejudicial, and if there is can you describe what that would be?", "start": 608.18, "stop": 625.373, "duration": 17.19}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric J. Feigin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Certainly, Your Honor.", "start": 625.373, "stop": 626.975, "duration": 1.6}, {"text": "We -- the government loses many of these cases even in circuits that have prejudice analysis.", "start": 626.975, "stop": 632.712, "duration": 5.74}, {"text": "In fact, one example the Court might want to look to, there was a certiorari petition I think filed at the end of last term, a case, 11-8966, Rebollo-Andino, which was a case of Rule 11(c)(1) error.", "start": 632.712, "stop": 646.972, "duration": 14.26}, {"text": "The government conceded that even on a plain error analysis that that was prejudicial.", "start": 646.972, "stop": 650.674, "duration": 3.7}, {"text": "I can describe--", "start": 650.674, "stop": 652.709, "duration": 2.03}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "What -- what makes it prejudicial and this not?", "start": 652.709, "stop": 655.226, "duration": 2.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric J. Feigin", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, let me take -- let me take a different example.", "start": 655.226, "stop": 658.78, "duration": 3.55}, {"text": "The Fourth Circuit's decision in United States v. Bradley, the judge essentially told the defendants that he -- it boggled his mind that they were going to trial and kept essentially harassing them about why they were going to trial.", "start": 658.78, "stop": 670.338, "duration": 11.56}, {"text": "And, eventually, they said, all right, Your Honor, we are going to -- we're going to plead guilty.", "start": 670.338, "stop": 674.139, "duration": 3.8}, {"text": "I mean, that kind of thing obviously is going to be prejudicial.", "start": 674.139, "stop": 678.574, "duration": 4.43}, {"text": "But the advantage of a prejudice approach is it allows you to separate that kind of case from kinds of cases when there are less serious errors, or even a case where there is a fairly serious error -- and this case may fall within that category -- but there are facts and circumstances that indicate that the error didn't have a reasonable probability of affecting the defendant's decision to plead.", "start": 678.574, "stop": 699.255, "duration": 20.68}, {"text": "And while we're not asking the Court to resolve the prejudice analysis here in the first instance, we -- we're just asking the Court to remand the case to the court of appeals to do that, I think it's just worth noting that -- a couple of the factors.", "start": 699.255, "stop": 709.546, "duration": 10.29}, {"text": "One is that -- there was a 3-month break between the magistrate judge's comments and the entry of the plea, and a month into that a speedy trial motion was filed, which indicated at least some intent at that point to go to trial.", "start": 709.546, "stop": 721.52, "duration": 11.97}, {"text": "The plea and the sentencing occurred in front of the district judge, not the magistrate judge who made the comments.", "start": 721.52, "stop": 726.757, "duration": 5.24}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "On that point, do we know -- do we know if the district judge who did preside at the plea hearing knew about the episode with the magistrate 3 months earlier?", "start": 726.757, "stop": 740.315, "duration": 13.56}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric J. Feigin", "textObjs": [{"text": "I don't -- I'm not aware of anything in the record that reflects whether he did or did not.", "start": 740.315, "stop": 744.136, "duration": 3.82}, {"text": "There's never been an allegation that -- that he said something about them, or that he was aware of them or--", "start": 744.136, "stop": 749.354, "duration": 5.22}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "The same for the prosecutor?", "start": 749.354, "stop": 750.956, "duration": 1.6}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric J. Feigin", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Your Honor, my understanding is the government was not aware of this because it occurred in an ex parte hearing in which the government wasn't in attendance.", "start": 750.956, "stop": 758.443, "duration": 7.49}, {"text": "The government wasn't aware of it until the Eleventh Circuit conducted its own review of the record and asked for further briefing on the issue.", "start": 758.443, "stop": 764.447, "duration": 6}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Suppose there's a case where the -- the defendant would not have pled guilty without the court saying something inappropriate about it's a case where the defendant would be crazy to go to trial because the trial would lead to a much more severe sentence.", "start": 764.447, "stop": 781.909, "duration": 17.46}, {"text": "Would there be prejudice there?", "start": 781.909, "stop": 782.927, "duration": 1.02}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric J. Feigin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, Your Honor.", "start": 782.927, "stop": 783.677, "duration": 0.75}, {"text": "He has a right to go to trial if he wants to go to trial, even if it would be crazy.", "start": 783.677, "stop": 787.229, "duration": 3.55}, {"text": "So under that circumstance, if he wouldn't have, you know, pleaded guilty without the erroneous comments from the judge, there would be prejudice.", "start": 787.229, "stop": 793.45, "duration": 6.22}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's -- what happens under -- under the rule if the magistrate asked that the defendant be excused -- I don't know quite how you do that; the defendant has to be present.", "start": 793.45, "stop": 805.524, "duration": 12.07}, {"text": "But can the -- can the judge just have the attorneys before him and say, now, I want you to be very, very clear that this is a mandatory minimum, that we should try to avoid if at all possible.", "start": 805.524, "stop": 818.784, "duration": 13.26}, {"text": "Can he do that?", "start": 818.784, "stop": 819.634, "duration": 0.85}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric J. Feigin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, Your Honor, I think that's--", "start": 819.634, "stop": 822.219, "duration": 2.59}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "It's awfully hard to have a hypothetical where you exclude the defendant.", "start": 822.219, "stop": 824.521, "duration": 2.3}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric J. Feigin", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, Your Honor, this actually happened in a non-hypothetical fashion in a case we cite in our reply brief, called In re United States, in which the judge was apparently unhappy with the Government's conduct in that case and had the prosecutor and defense counsel in chambers, or at least in court, without the defendant's presence, and was urging the parties to reach a plea agreement.", "start": 824.521, "stop": 844.667, "duration": 20.15}, {"text": "I think if something like that happens, Your Honor, there'd be some question whether the defendant was made aware of it, and whether it actually influenced the defendant's decision to plead.", "start": 844.667, "stop": 853.273, "duration": 8.61}, {"text": "I don't think there can be a presumption that just because counsel heard it, that necessarily--", "start": 853.273, "stop": 857.559, "duration": 4.29}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "What -- what if the judge sees what the judge thinks is ineffective assistance of counsel under our decision in Lafler taking place?", "start": 857.559, "stop": 866.931, "duration": 9.37}, {"text": "Is there anything that can be done?", "start": 866.931, "stop": 868.45, "duration": 1.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric J. Feigin", "textObjs": [{"text": "--So -- Your Honor, I think one of our main concerns in bringing this case before the Court is the interaction of this Court's decisions in Lafler and Frye with Rule 11(c)(1), and Frye suggests that one way a judge can try to guard against a later claim of ineffective assistance of counsel is to conduct a colloquy with the defendant -- not a colloquy, but a discussion with the defendant -- during the initial proceedings to try to establish that he understands the consequences of his plea and that he's receiving effective assistance of counsel.", "start": 868.45, "stop": 899.486, "duration": 31.04}, {"text": "I think that could be done very carefully by asking very general questions, but I think it's very easy to see how a judge might slip up and say, oh, that's an interesting offer.", "start": 899.486, "stop": 908.175, "duration": 8.69}, {"text": "Did you discuss that with your counsel?", "start": 908.175, "stop": 909.777, "duration": 1.6}, {"text": "That seems like something you ought to discuss with your counsel.", "start": 909.777, "stop": 911.894, "duration": 2.12}, {"text": "And I think what the automatic reversal rule the court of appeals has adopted is it really puts judges, and, frankly, the government, in kind of a box.", "start": 911.894, "stop": 918.965, "duration": 7.07}, {"text": "On the one hand, judges have to guard against these later ineffective assistance of counsel claims by discussing plea discussions, and on the other hand, any slipup in that discussion is going to lead to automatic reversal on appeal.", "start": 918.965, "stop": 930.773, "duration": 11.81}, {"text": "Now, I -- I just want to add one -- one more thing, which is, I think, the best evidence that we have that this -- the magistrate judge's comments here did not create a reasonable probability of effecting the defendant's decision to plead is, again, defendant himself moved pro se to withdraw his plea in the district court, and his reasons for withdrawing his plea, which start on page 58 of the Joint Appendix, never mention the magistrate's comments.", "start": 930.773, "stop": 956.424, "duration": 25.65}, {"text": "Instead, in his own words, what he says is,", "start": 956.424, "stop": 958.44, "duration": 2.02}, {"text": "\"Your Honor, my decision to enter the plea was a strategic decision. \"", "start": 958.44, "stop": 962.059, "duration": 3.62}, {"text": "\"The reason being is that I knew that the prosecutor had a duty with the courts to disclose the information relevant for this court's determination of the acceptance or rejection of the plea. \"", "start": 962.059, "stop": 971.434, "duration": 9.38}, {"text": "And what he means by that is that he took issue with some aspects of the allegations in the indictment, although he's quite clear, both in that proceeding and at his guilty plea proceeding, that he did commit the conspiracy offense, and he just believed that those allegations in the record would be cleaned up or have to be withdrawn by the prosecutor if he pleaded guilty.", "start": 971.434, "stop": 990.646, "duration": 19.21}, {"text": "Now, he was wrong about that.", "start": 990.646, "stop": 992.181, "duration": 1.54}, {"text": "But what we have in this case is a clear unvarnished explanation by the defendant in his own words about why he pleaded that doesn't mention the magistrate's comments.", "start": 992.181, "stop": 1001.536, "duration": 9.35}, {"text": "The Court of Appeals erred in disregarding that.", "start": 1001.536, "stop": 1004.488, "duration": 2.95}, {"text": "And if the Court has no more questions, I'll reserve the balance of my time.", "start": 1004.488, "stop": 1007.523, "duration": 3.03}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you, counsel.", "start": 1007.523, "stop": 1008.407, "duration": 0.88}, {"text": "Mr. Yablon?", "start": 1008.407, "stop": 1014.927, "duration": 6.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Robert M. Yablon", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court:", "start": 1014.927, "stop": 1018.045, "duration": 3.12}, {"text": "By imploring Anthony Davila to forego his trial rights, confess his alleged crimes, and accept a plea deal, the magistrate judge abandoned his role as neutral arbiter and fundamentally distorted the pretrial process.", "start": 1018.045, "stop": 1031.703, "duration": 13.66}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "I -- I don't want to interrupt your opening because I think -- I just didn't hear your first -- “ by foregoing ”?", "start": 1031.703, "stop": 1038.274, "duration": 6.57}]}, {"speakerName": "Robert M. Yablon", "textObjs": [{"text": "By foregoing--", "start": 1038.274, "stop": 1038.876, "duration": 0.6}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "By foregoing.", "start": 1038.876, "stop": 1039.493, "duration": 0.62}]}, {"speakerName": "Robert M. Yablon", "textObjs": [{"text": "--his trial rights.", "start": 1039.493, "stop": 1040.643, "duration": 1.15}, {"text": "This -- the right at issue in this case is not one that should be subject to post hoc speculation.", "start": 1040.643, "stop": 1050.516, "duration": 9.87}, {"text": "Judges, when an error of this kind occurs--", "start": 1050.516, "stop": 1053.552, "duration": 3.04}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "You're creating a sui generis structural error analysis.", "start": 1053.552, "stop": 1059.289, "duration": 5.74}, {"text": "You're basically -- because even with respect to constitutional violations that we have found structural error in, we've created the plain error rule that still requires a proof of prejudice.", "start": 1059.289, "stop": 1074.049, "duration": 14.76}, {"text": "So you're asking us to create something that's really sui generis in saying it's always a structural error.", "start": 1074.049, "stop": 1081.302, "duration": 7.25}]}, {"speakerName": "Robert M. Yablon", "textObjs": [{"text": "--That's -- that's not correct, Your Honor.", "start": 1081.302, "stop": 1083.321, "duration": 2.02}, {"text": "First, let's put to one side the fact that we do argue that we should not be in a plain error framework at all in this case because of the circumstances in which the judge's improper intervention occurred.", "start": 1083.321, "stop": 1092.76, "duration": 9.44}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "Assume I accept that argument.", "start": 1092.76, "stop": 1093.643, "duration": 0.88}]}, {"speakerName": "Robert M. Yablon", "textObjs": [{"text": "So this Court has--", "start": 1093.643, "stop": 1095.045, "duration": 1.4}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "You're -- you're saying this is a structural error always.", "start": 1095.045, "stop": 1097.379, "duration": 2.33}]}, {"speakerName": "Robert M. Yablon", "textObjs": [{"text": "--And this Court has, at the very least, strongly suggested that substantial rights when you're dealing with a structural error are affected, per se, where they've left the door open to some additional analysis is the fourth prong of the plain error standard where the Court is called upon to consider whether the error affects the fairness, integrity, or public reputation of the proceedings.", "start": 1097.379, "stop": 1120.261, "duration": 22.88}, {"text": "And the government has never, in this case, invoked that fourth prong.", "start": 1120.261, "stop": 1123.613, "duration": 3.35}, {"text": "They've never claimed that the error here is one that -- that does not affect the the fairness, integrity, or public reputation.", "start": 1123.613, "stop": 1130.385, "duration": 6.77}, {"text": "So when you're only dealing with the third prong of the plain error standard, does the error affect substantial rights, that language is the same in Rule 52(b), the plain error standard, as it is in Rule 52(a), affects substantial rights, and if it means in Rule 52(a) that this is the sort of error for which an individualized prejudice inquiry is not appropriate, then the same analysis necessarily carries over to Rule 52(b).", "start": 1130.385, "stop": 1156.168, "duration": 25.78}, {"text": "So I would not say that this is at all the kind of sui generis example that -- that you're indicating.", "start": 1156.168, "stop": 1161.672, "duration": 5.5}, {"text": "And I do want to -- to -- and try to show that this error is quite similar, both to constitutional and nonconstitutional violations in with -- which this Court has said that an error should be said to affect substantial rights without the sort of specific showing of prejudice that the government is demanding.", "start": 1161.672, "stop": 1181.068, "duration": 19.4}, {"text": "When you have a judge that, as in this case, is stepping out of his proper role, is acting contrary to his duties to guard against ill-considered and involuntary waivers of the defendant's basic trial rights, is actually ratcheting up the already tremendous pressure on the defendant to plead guilty, that is a systematic distortion of the process.", "start": 1181.068, "stop": 1203.065, "duration": 22}, {"text": "That is not unlike the kind of error that occurs when a defendant is denied an impartial adjudicator.", "start": 1203.065, "stop": 1209.92, "duration": 6.86}, {"text": "It is not unlike the kind of error that occurs when a defendant is denied counsel or is forced to--", "start": 1209.92, "stop": 1215.139, "duration": 5.22}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "What -- what if you have the situation where the judge is conveying purely factual information?", "start": 1215.139, "stop": 1220.36, "duration": 5.22}, {"text": "There's a -- a plea bargain on the table for one year and the judge says, you should know that I -- I have these cases a lot.", "start": 1220.36, "stop": 1228.716, "duration": 8.36}, {"text": "The last ten cases that went to trial where the defendant was found guilty, I sentenced them to a minimum of 12 years.", "start": 1228.716, "stop": 1234.703, "duration": 5.99}, {"text": "Pure facts.", "start": 1234.703, "stop": 1236.738, "duration": 2.04}, {"text": "The facts might have the effect of pushing the defendant one way or another, but it's also factual information of which he ought to be aware.", "start": 1236.738, "stop": 1248.027, "duration": 11.29}]}, {"speakerName": "Robert M. Yablon", "textObjs": [{"text": "--That's right, Your Honor, and this raises a question about what the scope of the participation prohibition actually is.", "start": 1248.027, "stop": 1254.949, "duration": 6.92}, {"text": "And we're in a strange posture in this case because the government has conceded that we're dealing with a conceded plain violation of the rule, and yet their analysis, instead of proceeding from that violation, it goes out to the periphery and tries to figure out where are the boundaries of Rule 11.", "start": 1254.949, "stop": 1269.709, "duration": 14.76}, {"text": "Now -- and they cite some appellate cases that arguably have applied too broad a construction of the rule and have reversed where maybe there was just a one-off comment or a purely informational comment, but it's not clear that that is actually what the text of Rule 11 forbids, particularly when you consider the context of the rule and its underlying purposes.", "start": 1269.709, "stop": 1290.122, "duration": 20.41}, {"text": "So--", "start": 1290.122, "stop": 1290.572, "duration": 0.45}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, we do need to have a good sense of how far your -- your per se structural argument is going to reach before we decide -- in deciding whether it's appropriate or not.", "start": 1290.572, "stop": 1300.312, "duration": 9.74}]}, {"speakerName": "Robert M. Yablon", "textObjs": [{"text": "--That's right, Your Honor, and there are -- there are two ways to break it down.", "start": 1300.312, "stop": 1303.097, "duration": 2.79}, {"text": "One is we do argue that the remedy that we seek should apply for all cases of judicial participation.", "start": 1303.097, "stop": 1310.286, "duration": 7.19}, {"text": "And the question then is: Are judicial participation violations as expansive a category as the government suggests that they are?", "start": 1310.286, "stop": 1317.44, "duration": 7.15}, {"text": "Our second argument is that--", "start": 1317.44, "stop": 1319.476, "duration": 2.04}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, on that, what's the most minor thing that the government could do that would still count as a Rule 11(c)(1) violation?", "start": 1319.476, "stop": 1326.296, "duration": 6.82}]}, {"speakerName": "Robert M. Yablon", "textObjs": [{"text": "--The most minor thing that the government could do or a judge could do?", "start": 1326.296, "stop": 1329.414, "duration": 3.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "That the judge could do.", "start": 1329.414, "stop": 1329.947, "duration": 0.53}, {"text": "I'm sorry.", "start": 1329.947, "stop": 1330.481, "duration": 0.53}]}, {"speakerName": "Robert M. Yablon", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, the most minor -- we think that Rule 11 is concerned with judicial pressure to plead guilty.", "start": 1330.481, "stop": 1335.818, "duration": 5.34}, {"text": "And so the most -- I mean, a judge might make a comment that, viewed from the transcript, would suggest that the evidence against the defendant is overwhelming or that the defendant is likely to get a much lower sentence if he pleads guilty than if he goes to trial.", "start": 1335.818, "stop": 1351.345, "duration": 15.53}, {"text": "Those we think are--", "start": 1351.345, "stop": 1352.447, "duration": 1.1}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "What -- what about the hypothetical that I posed?", "start": 1352.447, "stop": 1355.582, "duration": 3.14}]}, {"speakerName": "Robert M. Yablon", "textObjs": [{"text": "--So that hypothetical, if -- if we were talking about a purely informational statement like that, then, actually, we don't think that that is likely to be a violation of Rule 11(c)(1).", "start": 1355.582, "stop": 1367.956, "duration": 12.37}, {"text": "And the reason is, if you look at 11(b), the rule expects that judges are, in fact, going to be offering a lot of advice to defendants before the defendant pleads guilty.", "start": 1367.956, "stop": 1378.014, "duration": 10.06}, {"text": "And so if a judge is making the kinds of comments that Rule 11(b) is contemplating, informing the defendant about the nature of the charges against him, attempting to make sure that the defendant understands that his trial right is a real one, telling the defendant a little bit about what, in fact, the -- the sentencing exposure might be if he is convicted, those purely informational statements we don't think is what is meant to be prohibited by the rule.", "start": 1378.014, "stop": 1403.546, "duration": 25.53}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "So if he -- if it's my example and he says, this is what I've done the past ten times, so you ought to think long and hard about whether a bargain for one year is a good deal.", "start": 1403.546, "stop": 1412.168, "duration": 8.62}]}, {"speakerName": "Robert M. Yablon", "textObjs": [{"text": "So -- and -- and this is getting -- and then the judge may well be crossing the line.", "start": 1412.168, "stop": 1417.805, "duration": 5.64}, {"text": "And what the judge--", "start": 1417.805, "stop": 1418.672, "duration": 0.87}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "It's kind of a fine line to -- to draw, isn't it?", "start": 1418.672, "stop": 1421.591, "duration": 2.92}]}, {"speakerName": "Robert M. Yablon", "textObjs": [{"text": "--There's no question that there will be close cases.", "start": 1421.591, "stop": 1424.226, "duration": 2.64}, {"text": "I would say that if you look to the majority of cases that are actually out there, most judges, of course, are very scrupulous about following the rule.", "start": 1424.226, "stop": 1431.149, "duration": 6.92}, {"text": "And when a judge is not, the judge is not usually being circumspect about it, the judge is trying to get a message across to the defendant.", "start": 1431.149, "stop": 1437.969, "duration": 6.82}, {"text": "And so there may be difficult line-drawing cases, and that's true whether you're looking at the remedial approach that we're asking for or the remedial approach that the Government's asking for.", "start": 1437.969, "stop": 1446.825, "duration": 8.86}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Yablon, the -- the case that you're presenting would be quite strong if the same judge -- if the magistrate judge also presided at the plea hearing, but here we have two factors that are special in this case.", "start": 1446.825, "stop": 1468.172, "duration": 21.35}, {"text": "One is it's a different judge, and two is we have the interval of some three months in between.", "start": 1468.172, "stop": 1477.361, "duration": 9.19}, {"text": "And then we have a plea hearing that looks to me like it's exemplary.", "start": 1477.361, "stop": 1484.45, "duration": 7.09}, {"text": "The district judge did go through everything that Rule 11 calls for.", "start": 1484.45, "stop": 1489.001, "duration": 4.55}, {"text": "So it is a different case, isn't it, when we have a plea hearing with a judge who is exerting no pressure at all, has nothing to do with encouraging the defendant to plead, but there was an earlier episode where a magistrate judge did overbear?", "start": 1489.001, "stop": 1512.701, "duration": 23.7}]}, {"speakerName": "Robert M. Yablon", "textObjs": [{"text": "And at no point during the plea colloquy hearing is the district judge in any way acknowledging or disavowing the magistrate judge's comments, which, we submit, there is at least a very strong probability that those comments affected the defendant's thinking and the reason that the defendant is at the Rule 11 hearing in the first place.", "start": 1512.701, "stop": 1531.68, "duration": 18.98}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "But -- but the -- but the judge did ask, do you recognize that your -- your conduct satisfied the elements of the conspiracy?", "start": 1531.68, "stop": 1540.62, "duration": 8.94}, {"text": "And the defendant answered yes.", "start": 1540.62, "stop": 1543.053, "duration": 2.43}, {"text": "And the -- the judge asked, has anyone pressured you to plead guilty?", "start": 1543.053, "stop": 1550.642, "duration": 7.59}, {"text": "And he answers no.", "start": 1550.642, "stop": 1552.059, "duration": 1.42}, {"text": "So--", "start": 1552.059, "stop": 1553.861, "duration": 1.8}]}, {"speakerName": "Robert M. Yablon", "textObjs": [{"text": "And, of course, in that situation, the defendant is likely not thinking about pressure that may come from the judiciary itself.", "start": 1553.861, "stop": 1561.7, "duration": 7.84}, {"text": "And also, not to nitpick but when he's asking that pressure question he's asking whether anyone pressured him to plead guilty today, which may not cause the defendant to think back on why he started down the negotiation road.", "start": 1561.7, "stop": 1574.007, "duration": 12.31}, {"text": "I think an important--", "start": 1574.007, "stop": 1574.974, "duration": 0.97}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Yablon, I agree with you totally.", "start": 1574.974, "stop": 1578.126, "duration": 3.15}, {"text": "I'm not as much convinced in the delay in pleading because defendants often think about it and I can imagine a hypothetical where the lawyer comes in and says: I told him to plead guilty and he said to me: I don't want to, but the judge told me to.", "start": 1578.126, "stop": 1593.588, "duration": 15.46}, {"text": "So I don't think the time limit -- we don't know if that happened.", "start": 1593.588, "stop": 1596.723, "duration": 3.13}, {"text": "But what did happen is that the defendant made a motion to withdraw his plea and he directly said:", "start": 1596.723, "stop": 1604.294, "duration": 7.57}, {"text": "\"I entered the plea because I strategically decided that the government would eventually have to come forward and vacate the charges against me. \"", "start": 1604.294, "stop": 1617.286, "duration": 12.99}, {"text": "He said it himself with no pressure by a lawyer, because he was making the motion.", "start": 1617.286, "stop": 1622.672, "duration": 5.39}, {"text": "How do you get past that statement?", "start": 1622.672, "stop": 1625.04, "duration": 2.37}]}, {"speakerName": "Robert M. Yablon", "textObjs": [{"text": "--That statement reveals just how little confidence we actually should have in the plea decision that he made.", "start": 1625.04, "stop": 1629.928, "duration": 4.89}, {"text": "Here is a defendant who for the better part of a year was adamant about his desire to go to trial and exercise his rights.", "start": 1629.928, "stop": 1635.915, "duration": 5.99}, {"text": "It's the reason that the in camera hearing happened in the first place, because he was unhappy that the lawyer just wanted him to plead guilty.", "start": 1635.915, "stop": 1642.486, "duration": 6.57}, {"text": "After that hearing, suddenly there are plea negotiations and a plea deal, which it's clear that he is never happy about from the start.", "start": 1642.486, "stop": 1649.758, "duration": 7.27}, {"text": "Even at the plea hearing, he is attempting to tell the judge: Look, I don't think that my conduct actually is consistent with the conspiracy charge as alleged.", "start": 1649.758, "stop": 1658.947, "duration": 9.19}, {"text": "And he says later at the sentencing hearing when they are discussing the withdrawal motion that basically he went forward because his lawyer was instructing him that it was the right thing to do.", "start": 1658.947, "stop": 1668.653, "duration": 9.71}, {"text": "And if you look at that sentencing--", "start": 1668.653, "stop": 1671.088, "duration": 2.43}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "But that is the whole point, which is this may be IAC, but I don't know how -- how you prove that what the magistrate judge said to him led to his decision.", "start": 1671.088, "stop": 1682.896, "duration": 11.81}]}, {"speakerName": "Robert M. Yablon", "textObjs": [{"text": "--And we don't need to prove that.", "start": 1682.896, "stop": 1684.146, "duration": 1.25}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's only if we don't accept that prejudice is a consideration here.", "start": 1684.146, "stop": 1690.65, "duration": 6.5}]}, {"speakerName": "Robert M. Yablon", "textObjs": [{"text": "Either way, if you were looking at whether this conduct should be viewed as inherently prejudicial the reason that you might do that is because you might think that at least in all of these cases there might at least be a reasonable probability that it would affect where the defendant is.", "start": 1690.65, "stop": 1703.041, "duration": 12.39}, {"text": "And here you have a defendant who has been adamant that he's not going to plead, and when you have the judge making these comments in front of the defendant, having him lose confidence in his right to go to trial, then it's likely that that is shifting the defendant's mind set in a way that gets him to the negotiating table.", "start": 1703.041, "stop": 1718.9, "duration": 15.86}, {"text": "And it also reaffirms the defense lawyer's position in this case.", "start": 1718.9, "stop": 1724.287, "duration": 5.39}, {"text": "And so you have a defense lawyer who may then go back to the prosecutor and say: We're just going to get this deal done, and it may not be the deal that the defendant would otherwise have wanted reached.", "start": 1724.287, "stop": 1734.327, "duration": 10.04}]}, {"speakerName": "Stephen G. Breyer", "textObjs": [{"text": "You want us to basically not apply the 11(h), the harmless error business, and you basically want to prevent bizarre results by making a tough definition of the word “ participate ”.", "start": 1734.327, "stop": 1747.737, "duration": 13.41}, {"text": "That's how I understand you.", "start": 1747.737, "stop": 1750.021, "duration": 2.28}, {"text": "And maybe you are right, but it sounds to me as you say it in reading the briefs that this is really a job for the rules committee.", "start": 1750.021, "stop": 1757.608, "duration": 7.59}, {"text": "This is a rule.", "start": 1757.608, "stop": 1759.227, "duration": 1.62}, {"text": "We don't normally have structural errors with respect to rules.", "start": 1759.227, "stop": 1762.329, "duration": 3.1}, {"text": "We have rules committees there to listen to this kind of complaint, to weigh it in the system as a whole and to come up with better rules.", "start": 1762.329, "stop": 1770.352, "duration": 8.02}]}, {"speakerName": "Robert M. Yablon", "textObjs": [{"text": "Let me address that in two ways, because we have two separate arguments and I want to try to keep them distinct.", "start": 1770.352, "stop": 1775.404, "duration": 5.05}, {"text": "One is that if you look at the text and the history of Rule 11, there is strong evidence that Congress actually made an affirmative judgment not to sweep in Rule 11 violations within the scope of Rule 11(h).", "start": 1775.404, "stop": 1790.564, "duration": 15.16}, {"text": "Our second argument is even if Rule 11(h) applies to all Rule 11 errors, that all Rule 11(h) does is apply the same substantial rights language that you see in Rule 52(a) and (b).", "start": 1790.564, "stop": 1805.589, "duration": 15.02}, {"text": "And this Court has recognized that, while that substantial rights language is often synonymous with a case of specific prejudice inquiry, that's not always true.", "start": 1805.589, "stop": 1814.429, "duration": 8.84}, {"text": "And there are a number of examples.", "start": 1814.429, "stop": 1816.814, "duration": 2.38}, {"text": "The Court is familiar with the constitutional cases in which the Court has said that an error is structural without trying to determine, make a case-specific determination of prejudice.", "start": 1816.814, "stop": 1825.92, "duration": 9.11}, {"text": "But there are a number of nonconstitutional cases as well in which the Court has said an individualized prejudice inquiry is simply inappropriate, that the error affects substantial rights by its nature.", "start": 1825.92, "stop": 1836.71, "duration": 10.79}, {"text": "So one example that I think is fairly close to the one we have here is Gomez v. United States, where you have the Court addressing a statutory provision that prevents magistrate judges from conducting the jury voir dire and that proviso is violated and the Court is asked to conduct a prejudice analysis: Did it matter that the magistrate judge conducted voir dire?", "start": 1836.71, "stop": 1861.076, "duration": 24.37}, {"text": "And the Court said: We are not going to go there; this is in effect a structural defect in the proceedings.", "start": 1861.076, "stop": 1868.016, "duration": 6.94}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, Mr. Yablon, have we ever said that about the violation of a rule of criminal procedure, that it's structural error no matter what the circumstances?", "start": 1868.016, "stop": 1874.835, "duration": 6.82}]}, {"speakerName": "Robert M. Yablon", "textObjs": [{"text": "First, Justice Sotomayor, this Court has said that rules of criminal -- I'm so, sorry--", "start": 1874.835, "stop": 1879.906, "duration": 5.07}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's not the first time that has happened.", "start": 1879.906, "stop": 1885.125, "duration": 5.22}]}, {"speakerName": "Robert M. Yablon", "textObjs": [{"text": "--And I should be--", "start": 1885.125, "stop": 1886.727, "duration": 1.6}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "You worked for her, too, I think.", "start": 1886.727, "stop": 1887.86, "duration": 1.13}]}, {"speakerName": "Robert M. Yablon", "textObjs": [{"text": "--That makes it that much more embarrassing.", "start": 1887.86, "stop": 1890.445, "duration": 2.59}, {"text": "She used to sit over there.", "start": 1890.445, "stop": 1894.833, "duration": 4.39}, {"text": "This Court has said that Federal rules and statutes stand on equal footing, so whether we are talking about applying this with respect to a rule or a statute, it shouldn't make a difference; the analysis should be the same.", "start": 1894.833, "stop": 1910.343, "duration": 15.51}, {"text": "And in fact there is at least one case where the Court did apply in effect the structural analysis to -- to a rule violation and a second case in which the Court at least left open the possibility.", "start": 1910.343, "stop": 1924.352, "duration": 14.01}, {"text": "So the case in which the Court did so is the McCarthy case, which is discussed extensively in the briefs.", "start": 1924.352, "stop": 1929.97, "duration": 5.62}, {"text": "The Court referred to the 1966 version of Rule 11 and said that prejudice adheres in a violation of that rule and that it was not going to conduct an individualized analysis.", "start": 1929.97, "stop": 1941.612, "duration": 11.64}, {"text": "It was simply going to grant relief where there had not been full compliance with that provision.", "start": 1941.612, "stop": 1947.282, "duration": 5.67}, {"text": "Of course, the rule has been amended since then, but that provides evidence that the Court is not unwilling to adopt this kind of rule in the context of the Federal Rules.", "start": 1947.282, "stop": 1956.721, "duration": 9.44}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "I would think, Mr. Yablon, that one of the effects of what you are asking us to do is that the rule would just get narrower and narrower.", "start": 1956.721, "stop": 1964.227, "duration": 7.51}, {"text": "In other words, if automatic reversal is always the effect of finding a violation -- and I think you acknowledge this in a way -- that people will just find fewer and fewer violations.", "start": 1964.227, "stop": 1975.118, "duration": 10.89}, {"text": "And I'm wondering why we should do something like that rather than interpret the rule as it was meant to be interpreted, but then say: You know, somebody can look and say it really just didn't matter that it was violated in this case.", "start": 1975.118, "stop": 1988.943, "duration": 13.83}]}, {"speakerName": "Robert M. Yablon", "textObjs": [{"text": "So we think that our approach is consistent with how the rule is in fact meant to be interpreted.", "start": 1988.943, "stop": 1994.163, "duration": 5.22}, {"text": "The rule really is about this problem of placing judicial pressure on defendants to plead guilty, and those are the cases that ought to be reversed.", "start": 1994.163, "stop": 2001.935, "duration": 7.77}, {"text": "But the Court has a line-drawing decision to make either way.", "start": 2001.935, "stop": 2005.72, "duration": 3.79}, {"text": "Either the line that the Court should focus on is the line that separates participation from nonparticipation or, again, a narrower class of participation.", "start": 2005.72, "stop": 2014.843, "duration": 9.12}, {"text": "And I want to get to this point that--", "start": 2014.843, "stop": 2017.445, "duration": 2.6}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "But you are arguing for a narrower interpretation of Rule 11(c)(1) than a number of courts of appeals have adopted, isn't that correct?", "start": 2017.445, "stop": 2025.051, "duration": 7.61}]}, {"speakerName": "Robert M. Yablon", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I believe there are some decisions out that have adopted probably a broader construction than we think is necessary and appropriate.", "start": 2025.051, "stop": 2032.288, "duration": 7.24}, {"text": "But what is easier for reviewing courts to monitor?", "start": 2032.288, "stop": 2036.775, "duration": 4.49}, {"text": "Is it easier for them to monitor the narrowing, the improper narrowing of the rule over time, or is it easier for them to monitor improper applications of the harmless error rule, especially applications of it that are happening in this kind of setting, where it's going to be almost inherently a very speculative analysis, an attempt to read the defendant's mind and ascertain whether the defendant was influenced by what the judge was saying.", "start": 2036.775, "stop": 2062.391, "duration": 25.62}, {"text": "And it would be much easier for appellate courts to focus on the line-drawing exercise that determines whether or not a violation had occurred or, if you think that the rule is broader, whether the kind of violation that occurred in this case occurred, than it would be to try to make this case-by-case scouring the record, individualized prejudice determinations.", "start": 2062.391, "stop": 2085.339, "duration": 22.95}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Could you say something about Mr. Feigin's comments regarding what a judge can and cannot do if the judge thinks that he or she sees a violation of Lafler and Frye taking place?", "start": 2085.339, "stop": 2100.782, "duration": 15.44}]}, {"speakerName": "Robert M. Yablon", "textObjs": [{"text": "So there ought to be things that a judge is able to do in that situation.", "start": 2100.782, "stop": 2106.686, "duration": 5.9}, {"text": "Suppose, for example, that the judge becomes aware that the defense attorney has given the -- his client false information about the elements of the charge.", "start": 2106.686, "stop": 2116.458, "duration": 9.77}, {"text": "It would not violate Rule 11(c)(1) for the judge to say: I understand that you were told that the elements of the charge are A, B, and C, but in fact they are X, Y, and Z.", "start": 2116.458, "stop": 2127.063, "duration": 10.61}, {"text": "So there are -- there are certainly steps that a judge can take to help root out the violation.", "start": 2127.063, "stop": 2133.586, "duration": 6.52}, {"text": "And I would say that the fact is that generally when it comes to ineffective assistance of counsel claims there is only so much that the trial could court can do.", "start": 2133.586, "stop": 2143.442, "duration": 9.86}, {"text": "So the fact that the trial court may not be able to solve or prevent every ineffective assistance claim in this context is not necessarily an argument against the rule, because the judge often is not aware of the privileged communications.", "start": 2143.442, "stop": 2156.517, "duration": 13.07}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "What if the judge knows as a result of pretrial motions that the evidence in the case is very, very strong.", "start": 2156.517, "stop": 2163.772, "duration": 7.26}, {"text": "Let's say there's a -- there's been a motion to suppress extremely incriminating evidence and the motion has been denied, so the judge knows this is going to come in.", "start": 2163.772, "stop": 2172.728, "duration": 8.96}, {"text": "And the judge thinks if this comes in, there's virtually very little chance that the defendant is going to be acquitted, and yet the defendant -- and the judge knows that a plea bargain -- a plea offer was made and the defendant initially was going to take it, and then before it was accepted, it's rejected.", "start": 2172.728, "stop": 2190.34, "duration": 17.61}, {"text": "Is there anything a judge can do in that situation?", "start": 2190.34, "stop": 2192.292, "duration": 1.95}, {"text": "Just sit back and, you know, wait for the case to be -- to be reversed?", "start": 2192.292, "stop": 2198.529, "duration": 6.24}]}, {"speakerName": "Robert M. Yablon", "textObjs": [{"text": "Well, the judge's role in that situation is -- is not to step in as defense counsel or, in effect, as second prosecutor.", "start": 2198.529, "stop": 2210.336, "duration": 11.81}, {"text": "The judge -- I think that there may be ways in that case for the judge to try to alleviate the error without -- without crossing the line.", "start": 2210.336, "stop": 2219.275, "duration": 8.94}, {"text": "But when -- but when you start to make exceptions in that -- in that situation, you -- you go down the road of -- of the judge being the one who is evaluating the evidence and who is, in effect, potentially presuming the defendant's guilt.", "start": 2219.275, "stop": 2232.75, "duration": 13.47}, {"text": "And the judge--", "start": 2232.75, "stop": 2233.4, "duration": 0.65}]}, {"speakerName": "Samuel A. Alito, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "It just puts -- puts the judge in a very difficult position.", "start": 2233.4, "stop": 2235.969, "duration": 2.57}, {"text": "It could -- can the judge say, you -- do you realize that I denied your motion to suppress that wiretap?", "start": 2235.969, "stop": 2242.64, "duration": 6.67}, {"text": "And do you recognize that on that wiretap, you conceded that the loss in this case is $20 million, and do you know that under the sentencing guidelines, the sentence where the loss is $20 million is whatever it is, ten years in jail.", "start": 2242.64, "stop": 2255.865, "duration": 13.22}, {"text": "If the judge says all of that, has the judge violated Rule 11(c)(1)?", "start": 2255.865, "stop": 2260.952, "duration": 5.09}]}, {"speakerName": "Robert M. Yablon", "textObjs": [{"text": "--And if this is happening in the context of active discussions of whether the defendant should or should not take a plea, then that -- that may well cross the line.", "start": 2260.952, "stop": 2270.975, "duration": 10.02}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "I don't know when it can happen, because there's no colloquy when there's a guilty plea.", "start": 2270.975, "stop": 2277.981, "duration": 7.01}, {"text": "The colloquy happens when there's a not guilty plea.", "start": 2277.981, "stop": 2280.214, "duration": 2.23}]}, {"speakerName": "Robert M. Yablon", "textObjs": [{"text": "I think -- isn't it the opposite, Justice Kennedy?", "start": 2280.214, "stop": 2284.301, "duration": 4.09}, {"text": "The colloquy happens after the defendant--", "start": 2284.301, "stop": 2286.217, "duration": 1.92}]}, {"speakerName": "Anthony M. Kennedy", "textObjs": [{"text": "No, no -- you're correct.", "start": 2286.217, "stop": 2287.586, "duration": 1.37}, {"text": "You're correct.", "start": 2287.586, "stop": 2288.619, "duration": 1.03}]}, {"speakerName": "Robert M. Yablon", "textObjs": [{"text": "--So -- so taking -- so in that instance, again, you have a situation that may not be different from situations that arise in completely different contexts, where the attorney is doing something that's ineffective, for example, and the judge just doesn't know about it.", "start": 2288.619, "stop": 2303.346, "duration": 14.73}, {"text": "And -- and whether or not that can be cured in this -- in this setting of the -- of plea discussions, it's just a little bit tangential, I think, to the key issue.", "start": 2303.346, "stop": 2314.237, "duration": 10.89}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Now -- well, but you've answered a lot of these questions by saying, you know, it's hard to draw the line and, you know, maybe in that case, maybe in this case.", "start": 2314.237, "stop": 2320.725, "duration": 6.49}, {"text": "Most -- our precedents where we recognize structural error and -- and plain error are ones that are pretty easily categorized.", "start": 2320.725, "stop": 2331.115, "duration": 10.39}, {"text": "Did a magistrate conduct voir dire or did he not?", "start": 2331.115, "stop": 2333.682, "duration": 2.57}, {"text": "You know right away one way or the other.", "start": 2333.682, "stop": 2335.817, "duration": 2.14}, {"text": "Did he participate enough?", "start": 2335.817, "stop": 2338.352, "duration": 2.53}, {"text": "You know, well, if he told them how many times he sentenced people this way, it's not, but if he said you ought to -- you ought to pay attention to what I'm telling you when you'd consider whether to plea or not, well, then it is.", "start": 2338.352, "stop": 2348.308, "duration": 9.96}, {"text": "It -- it seems to me in the typical plain error cases, we're very -- the categories are very sharply defined.", "start": 2348.308, "stop": 2354.129, "duration": 5.82}]}, {"speakerName": "Robert M. Yablon", "textObjs": [{"text": "That's actually not accurate.", "start": 2354.129, "stop": 2356.831, "duration": 2.7}, {"text": "I would say, for example, take the defendant's right to self-representation.", "start": 2356.831, "stop": 2361.885, "duration": 5.05}, {"text": "And do you -- there may be obvious cases and when the defendant's right to self-representation has been clearly denied.", "start": 2361.885, "stop": 2366.705, "duration": 4.82}, {"text": "But there are going to be line-drawing problems when you're trying to figure out did standby counsel intervene so much that he denied that right.", "start": 2366.705, "stop": 2373.959, "duration": 7.25}, {"text": "Or similarly with the public trial, obviously, a court can be totally closed, but then there are going to be difficult cases when you have to decide whether the justifications for closing the courtroom are--", "start": 2373.959, "stop": 2383.648, "duration": 9.69}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "I would say in both of those examples, the line -- the gray area, if you were, is really quite narrow than here, where almost every time you've been asked a question about a difficult hypothetical, you say, well, maybe, maybe not.", "start": 2383.648, "stop": 2394.539, "duration": 10.89}, {"text": "And I think that's quite different than saying is the court closed or not or was the person -- you know, did he represent himself in fact or not.", "start": 2394.539, "stop": 2402.379, "duration": 7.84}, {"text": "And those just strike me as much easier cases.", "start": 2402.379, "stop": 2406.246, "duration": 3.87}]}, {"speakerName": "Robert M. Yablon", "textObjs": [{"text": "--And, of course, I'm being asked all of the difficult hypotheticals.", "start": 2406.246, "stop": 2410.198, "duration": 3.95}, {"text": "If you look at the cases that actually rise--", "start": 2410.198, "stop": 2412.15, "duration": 1.95}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Yes, but if you were -- if you were arguing whether or not it's -- it's categorical error when the magistrate conducts voir dire, it'd be pretty hard for somebody to come up with a tough hypothetical.", "start": 2412.15, "stop": 2420.773, "duration": 8.62}]}, {"speakerName": "Robert M. Yablon", "textObjs": [{"text": "--In that instance, yes.", "start": 2420.773, "stop": 2423.142, "duration": 2.37}, {"text": "But there certainly are instances in which the structural -- in which the Court has found structural error, even when there will be difficult line-drawing problems.", "start": 2423.142, "stop": 2430.212, "duration": 7.07}, {"text": "And--", "start": 2430.212, "stop": 2430.679, "duration": 0.47}]}, {"speakerName": "Ruth Bader Ginsburg", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Mr. Yablon, one problem with calling this structural error is that it's not so clear that this is a -- a bad thing.", "start": 2430.679, "stop": 2439.985, "duration": 9.31}, {"text": "That is, some States even today allow a judge to participate in plea bargaining, and the advisors -- the rules advisory committee -- said, when it -- when it framed this rule that some commentators had said it was quite -- quite a frequent thing that happened, that judges participated.", "start": 2439.985, "stop": 2466.821, "duration": 26.84}, {"text": "So it isn't like not having a public trial or not giving a person counsel of choice.", "start": 2466.821, "stop": 2474.725, "duration": 7.9}, {"text": "It's, this was -- this was something that still some jurisdictions think it's okay.", "start": 2474.725, "stop": 2481.747, "duration": 7.02}]}, {"speakerName": "Robert M. Yablon", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Your Honor, no jurisdiction endorses judicial exhortations to plead guilty.", "start": 2481.747, "stop": 2487.133, "duration": 5.39}, {"text": "And -- and so this Court can resolve the case just on that narrower basis, that there is a category of cases that clearly do involve direct judicial pressure.", "start": 2487.133, "stop": 2497.09, "duration": 9.96}, {"text": "And no State allows it, and those are clear violations of the rules.", "start": 2497.09, "stop": 2502.66, "duration": 5.57}, {"text": "So without needing to draw these other lines about how broad participation may reach, the Court can do that.", "start": 2502.66, "stop": 2508.814, "duration": 6.15}, {"text": "But even in those States, it's important to note that -- that the Federal system has made a different structural choice.", "start": 2508.814, "stop": 2516.135, "duration": 7.32}, {"text": "So whether or not it may violate the Constitution for States to have carefully tailored procedures that allow some type of judicial involvement, that's not the structure that the Federal system has chosen.", "start": 2516.135, "stop": 2527.709, "duration": 11.57}, {"text": "And when you're dealing with the structural choice that was made in Rule 11, that judges shall not, must not participate in plea discussions, that that is as elemental to the Federal system of plea bargaining that we have as many of the familiar elements of -- of the trial are.", "start": 2527.709, "stop": 2544.237, "duration": 16.53}, {"text": "And so, the fact that States have made -- made different structural choices does not mean that it's not a structural error here.", "start": 2544.237, "stop": 2552.241, "duration": 8}, {"text": "Now, I do want to get back to this line-drawing issue, because I think that this is not something that should trouble the Court too much, for a couple of reasons: First, in most cases, the line will not be that hard to draw when you consider the purpose of Rule 11(c)(1), which is reducing judicial pressure, and instances in which judges are stepping out of their role as impartial adjudicators, and when reviewing courts take that as the touchstone, there may be difficult cases, but they're going to be able to resolve most of them.", "start": 2552.241, "stop": 2581.946, "duration": 29.7}, {"text": "Now, if the Court feels like it may be difficult to do line drawing, and it is uncomfortable extending the rule, the remedy that we're seeking that far, it is entirely appropriate for the Court to -- to take out a subcategory of Rule 11(c)(1) violations.", "start": 2581.946, "stop": 2599.206, "duration": 17.26}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "But that seems a bit odd, don't you think, Mr. Yablon?", "start": 2599.206, "stop": 2601.674, "duration": 2.47}, {"text": "You know, you're saying, well, there are core violations as opposed to noncore violations.", "start": 2601.674, "stop": 2605.645, "duration": 3.97}, {"text": "I mean, presumably, that's part of what the Court would think about when it was doing prejudice analysis.", "start": 2605.645, "stop": 2610.696, "duration": 5.05}]}, {"speakerName": "Robert M. Yablon", "textObjs": [{"text": "It would factor into the prejudice analysis that the Court undertakes, but it also is a reason just to -- to draw the line.", "start": 2610.696, "stop": 2619.052, "duration": 8.36}, {"text": "I mean, this Court in -- in various instances has indicated that -- I mean, there are some -- some broad rules out there: The right to the assistance of counsel.", "start": 2619.052, "stop": 2627.641, "duration": 8.59}, {"text": "It comes in different shapes.", "start": 2627.641, "stop": 2629.041, "duration": 1.4}, {"text": "And the prejudice analysis that applies for a total denial of the right to counsel is different from the one that applies when you're dealing with mere deficiency in counsel's performance.", "start": 2629.041, "stop": 2637.264, "duration": 8.22}, {"text": "And there is -- and again, this is -- this is a comparative line-drawing problem.", "start": 2637.264, "stop": 2642.251, "duration": 4.99}, {"text": "Either you draw the line looking at what a violation is or looking at what a judicial exhortation is from the statement that is made, or you engage in this freewheeling speculation that the government wants engaged in, where you were trying to read the defendant's mind.", "start": 2642.251, "stop": 2656.827, "duration": 14.58}, {"text": "And that is simply not how harmless error analysis normally proceeds, where you have a closed universe of a record, you have specific criteria that are being applied, and you can posit what a reasonable juror is.", "start": 2656.827, "stop": 2668.485, "duration": 11.66}, {"text": "There is no reasonable defendant that can be posited in the same way, because defendants are idiosyncratic and are entitled to be idiosyncratic.", "start": 2668.485, "stop": 2677.324, "duration": 8.84}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Yablon, do you know of any case where there is one of these core violations, these exhortation cases, where the Court did not find prejudice?", "start": 2677.324, "stop": 2685.447, "duration": 8.12}]}, {"speakerName": "Robert M. Yablon", "textObjs": [{"text": "The answer is no, and that would be -- and we would urge the Court that if it does not accept our primary submission, that it make clear that judicial exhortations like this are highly unlikely to be harmless.", "start": 2685.447, "stop": 2701.689, "duration": 16.24}, {"text": "That is what the Fourth Circuit has done, the Fifth Circuit, the Seventh Circuit, the Tenth Circuit, the D.C. Circuit.", "start": 2701.689, "stop": 2706.36, "duration": 4.67}, {"text": "They are in effect applying a per se analysis, they're just not calling it that.", "start": 2706.36, "stop": 2710.212, "duration": 3.85}, {"text": "They are reversing in all of these cases.", "start": 2710.212, "stop": 2712.331, "duration": 2.12}, {"text": "And so, if this Court is uncomfortable calling it a per se rule, at least it should give very strong indications that comments like this cannot be written off, that they are highly likely, given the position of the judge relative to the defendant, to affect the defendant's thinking, to affect the way that the defense counsel approaches the case, and possibly the prosecution as well in those cases in which the prosecution is aware of the error.", "start": 2712.331, "stop": 2734.577, "duration": 22.25}, {"text": "And we would go further and say that if the Court were to go down this road, it would be useful for the Court to provide the additional guidance of holding that this particular type of error was not harmless.", "start": 2734.577, "stop": 2745.302, "duration": 10.72}, {"text": "That would send a signal to the lower courts that this conduct is clearly off limits, and it would give them an indication that the court means what it's saying, that these kind of comments, where a judge is exhorting a defendant to come to the cross, that he needs to plead guilty--", "start": 2745.302, "stop": 2760.062, "duration": 14.76}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "How do we -- if we're giving this guidance, what do we say about the fact that he had a different judge subsequent to this, that he filed a speedy trial motion after this coercion, to suggest that he wasn't coerced all that much.", "start": 2760.062, "stop": 2773.987, "duration": 13.93}, {"text": "Are we supposed to take all that into consideration, too?", "start": 2773.987, "stop": 2776.404, "duration": 2.42}]}, {"speakerName": "Robert M. Yablon", "textObjs": [{"text": "--You should say that those inferences are not adequate to overcome the inference that you draw from this type of participation, particularly here.", "start": 2776.404, "stop": 2783.343, "duration": 6.94}, {"text": "I mean, consider the change in judge.", "start": 2783.343, "stop": 2785.46, "duration": 2.12}, {"text": "The reason this hearing occurred before the magistrate judge is because the defendant sent a letter to the district court asking -- explaining his problems with his counsel.", "start": 2785.46, "stop": 2794.216, "duration": 8.76}, {"text": "He got a response from the magistrate judge.", "start": 2794.216, "stop": 2796.318, "duration": 2.1}, {"text": "So in the defendant's mind, the magistrate judge and the district court are effectively one and the same, and you would not want a system where district courts are encouraged to send these issues to magistrate judges, so magistrate judges can engage in these kind of comments, but then the district judge can basically just cleanse it.", "start": 2796.318, "stop": 2811.511, "duration": 15.19}, {"text": "It is going to affect the way that the process plays out.", "start": 2811.511, "stop": 2814.962, "duration": 3.45}, {"text": "Now, the speedy trial issue, if I may just -- we can equally draw the inference that that was only done because counsel wanted to put some pressure on the government to actually reach a deal.", "start": 2814.962, "stop": 2826.604, "duration": 11.64}, {"text": "And it is that kind of speculation that makes this error ill-suited to the kind of remedial analysis the government favors.", "start": 2826.604, "stop": 2832.943, "duration": 6.34}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you, counsel.", "start": 2832.943, "stop": 2833.76, "duration": 0.82}, {"text": "Mr. Feigin, 13 minutes.", "start": 2833.76, "stop": 2837.245, "duration": 3.48}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric J. Feigin", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you, Mr. Chief Justice.", "start": 2837.245, "stop": 2839.847, "duration": 2.6}, {"text": "I just want to make one quick point in response to the notion that we're asking for some form of new prejudice analysis here.", "start": 2839.847, "stop": 2846.851, "duration": 7}, {"text": "This is the exact same prejudice analysis from Dominguez Benitez, that looks whether there is a reasonable probability that the error affected the plea.", "start": 2846.851, "stop": 2853.773, "duration": 6.92}, {"text": "Unless the Court has any further questions, I will rest--", "start": 2853.773, "stop": 2857.558, "duration": 3.78}]}, {"speakerName": "Elena Kagan", "textObjs": [{"text": "Mr. Feigin, can I ask you the same question that I asked Mr. Yablon: Do you know of any cases where in these -- where there are really core violations, where a judge exhorts the defendant to plea it -- does the Court ever find that non-prejudicial?", "start": 2857.558, "stop": 2871.401, "duration": 13.84}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric J. Feigin", "textObjs": [{"text": "--I am aware of one or two State cases in which the court has looked at the passage of time as a reason why that kind of error wouldn't have been prejudicial.", "start": 2871.401, "stop": 2880.257, "duration": 8.86}, {"text": "But otherwise, I agree with Respondent that in the Federal courts of appeals, that does tend to get reversed.", "start": 2880.257, "stop": 2886.078, "duration": 5.82}, {"text": "And I think that supports the idea that if the Court adopts the normal prejudice approach, and reaffirms that approach in this case, that there's not really that--", "start": 2886.078, "stop": 2893.399, "duration": 7.32}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "Do you disagree with how the Fourth and Seventh Circuits and other circuits apply a prejudice analysis, but one that says that it's highly unlikely that you're not going to find prejudice?", "start": 2893.399, "stop": 2903.956, "duration": 10.56}, {"text": "Do you disagree with their analysis and approach?", "start": 2903.956, "stop": 2905.939, "duration": 1.98}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric J. Feigin", "textObjs": [{"text": "--Well, Your Honor, there -- my -- I'm not going to go so far as to endorse the results they've reached in every single case--", "start": 2905.939, "stop": 2912.293, "duration": 6.35}]}, {"speakerName": "Sonia Sotomayor", "textObjs": [{"text": "No.", "start": 2912.293, "stop": 2912.812, "duration": 0.52}]}, {"speakerName": "Eric J. Feigin", "textObjs": [{"text": "--but I think insofar as they approach the matter that -- you know, if there's a fairly serious error and the defendant pleads guilty right after that, that that's very likely absence of extenuating circumstances to be prejudicial; we don't have a problem with that.", "start": 2912.812, "stop": 2928.155, "duration": 15.34}, {"text": "Unless there are further questions--", "start": 2928.155, "stop": 2930.44, "duration": 2.28}]}, {"speakerName": "John G. Roberts, Jr.", "textObjs": [{"text": "Thank you, counsel.", "start": 2930.44, "stop": 2932.14, "duration": 1.7}, {"text": "Counsel.", "start": 2932.14, "stop": 2932.973, "duration": 0.83}, {"text": "The case is submitted.", "start": 2932.973, "stop": 2934.306, "duration": 1.33}]}]}], "decidedBy": "Roberts Court", "arguedOn": "Apr 15, 2013", "petitioner": "United States", "respondent": "Anthony Davila", "docket": "12-167", "citation": "569 US 597 (2013)", "justiaLink": "https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/569/597", "lowerCourt": "United States Court of Appeals for the Eleventh Circuit", "grantedOn": "Jan 4, 2013", "decidedOn": "Jun 13, 2013", "wikiData": {"title": "United States v. Davila", "Litigants": "United States v. Davila", "ArgueDate": "April 15", "ArgueYear": "2013", "DecideDate": "June 13", "DecideYear": "2013", "FullName": "United States, Petitioner v. Anthony Davila", "USVol": "569", "USPage": "597", "ParallelCitations": "133 S. Ct. 2139; 186 [[L. Ed. 2d]] 139; 2013 [[U.S. LEXIS]] 4541; 81 U.S.L.W. 4394", "Docket": "12-167", "OralArgument": "https://www.oyez.org/cases/2010-2019/2012/2012_12_167/argument", "Prior": "664 [[F.3d]] [https://www.leagle.com/decision/infco20111221102 1355] ([[11th Cir.]] 2011)", "Subsequent": "", "Holding": "", "SCOTUS": "2010–2016", "Majority": "Ginsburg", "JoinMajority": "Roberts, Kennedy, Breyer, Alito, Sotomayor, Kagan", "Concurrence": "Scalia", "JoinConcurrence": "Thomas", "LawsApplied": ""}}